Kraydel could help millions of people in care worldwide. Please vote for us in @pitchatpalace audience choice award: http:// pitchatpalace.com/vote/
Kraydel can't predict falls just yet, but at least you’ll know when they’ve happened, and be able to respond.

The power of technology to predict and detect issues in the homes of the elderly is amazing: http://www. telegraph.co.uk/news/2017/02/1 7/scientists-find-way-predictolder-peoples-falls-three-weeks-happen/ …
Remote care for the vulnerable is clearly inevitable but we need to make it affordable and simple: https://www. disabilityscoop.com/2017/03/15/rem ote-monitoring-direct-support/23453/ …
4 or 5 rushed visits throughout a day could instead be 1 longer sit-down visit - less pressure for carers, more quality time for the elder.
Innovations like Kraydel can greatly reduce the number of visits a caregiver needs to make each day, without reducing the quality of care.
Our hearts go out to the dedicated people working domiciliary care right now. Much more needs to be done to help. http://www. bbc.co.uk/news/uk-wales- 39321818 …
Deploying Kraydel would allow patients to go home much earlier, and mean significant savings for healthcare providers. How about it @NHS ? :)
Heard on morning news that bed blocking" costs @NHS over £1,000 per patient, per week. Kraydel costs £200, and less than £10 per week. :)"
